# 2. Microservices Architecture

==================================================

Microservices is an **architectural design pattern where an application is divided into multiple small independent services**.

Each service:

• Handles a specific business functionality
• Runs independently
• Communicates via APIs

-------------------
## Important Points
------------------

Microservices is:

• NOT a technology
• NOT a framework
• NOT a programming language

Microservices **is an Architectural Design Pattern**.

It can be implemented using:

• Java
• Python
• NodeJS
• Go
• .NET

=======================================

## Microservices Architecture Diagram

=======================================

```
                +-------------------+
                |       Client      |
                +---------+---------+
                          |
                          v
                 +------------------+
                 |   API Gateway    |
                 +--------+---------+
                          |
       --------------------------------------------
       |            |            |                |
       v            v            v                v

+--------------+ +--------------+ +--------------+ +--------------+
| User Service | | Order Service| | Payment Serv | | Product Serv |
+--------------+ +--------------+ +--------------+ +--------------+
       |               |                |               |
       v               v                v               v

   +--------+      +--------+      +--------+      +--------+
   |  DB    |      |  DB    |      |  DB    |      |  DB    |
   +--------+      +--------+      +--------+      +--------+
```

Each service:

• Independent
• Own database
• Independent deployment

==================================================

# Advantages of Microservices Architecture

==================================================

---------------------
## 1. Loose Coupling
---------------------

Services are independent.

Failure in one service does not affect others.

Example

```
Payment Service down
→ User Service still works
```

---------------------------
## 2. Reduced Server Burden
---------------------------

Services are distributed across servers.

Load is balanced.

-----------------------
## 3. Easy Maintenance
-----------------------

Each service has **small codebase**.

Developers can maintain easily.

--------------------------------
## 4. No Single Point of Failure
--------------------------------

If one service fails

Other services continue working.

------------------
## 5. Scalability
------------------

We can scale **only the required service**.

Example

```
High traffic on Payment Service

Scale only Payment Service
```

----------------------------------
## 6. Technology Independence
----------------------------------

Each microservice can use different technology.

Example

```
User Service → Java
Payment Service → NodeJS
Notification Service → Python
```

----------------------------------
## 7. Faster Development & Delivery
----------------------------------

Multiple teams can work on different services simultaneously.

==================================================

# Challenges With Microservices Architecture

==================================================

---------------------
## 1. Bounded Context
----------------------

Deciding

• How many microservices
• Which functionality belongs to which service

Requires strong domain understanding.

---------------------------
## 2. Repeated Configuration
---------------------------

Every microservice requires configuration such as

• Database
• Security
• Kafka
• Logging
• Monitoring

Configuration duplication may occur.

-------------------------=
## 3. Service Visibility
-------------------------

In large systems it becomes difficult to know

```
Which service provides which functionality
```

To solve this we use

• Service Registry
• Documentation
• Monitoring tools

